<subsubsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title> Showing Separable I </title>

    <p>
        Most differential equations will not be presented in separable form, so you will need to use algebra to transform the equation into this form. In this module, we will cover various algebra techniques that can help separate the variables by multiplication. Mathematically, this looks like
        <me>
            \frac{dy}{dx} = \underset{not\ separated}{\underbrace{h(x, y)}} \quad \overset{algebra}{\longrightarrow} \quad \frac{dy}{dx} = \underset{separated}{\underbrace{f(x) \cdot g(y)}}
        </me>
        where <m>h(x, y)</m> represents the unseparated form of the two variables.
    </p>
    
    <example xml:id="example-separate-by-factoring"><title> Separate by Factoring </title>
    
        <p>
            Write the differential equation in separable form.
            <me> \frac{dy}{dx} = x + xy^2 </me>
        </p>
        
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since <m>x</m> is common in both terms of the sum, we can factor it out as
                <me>
                    \frac{dy}{dx} = \underset{not\ separated}{\underbrace{x + xy^2}}
                    \quad \overset{algebra}{\longrightarrow} \quad 
                    \frac{dy}{dx} = \underset{separated}{\underbrace{
                        {\color{blue} x } ({\color{green} 1 + y^2 })
                    }}
                </me>
                showing that the differential equation is <em>separable</em>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    
    </example>
    
    <example xml:id="example-separate-as-a-product-of-fractions"><title> Separate as a Product of Fractions </title>
    
        <p>
            Write the differential equation in separable form.
            <me> \frac{dP}{dt} = \frac{Pt}{P^2 + 1} </me>
        </p>
        
        <solution>
            <p>
                This example uses the following rule for multiplying fractions:
                <me>
                    \frac{A\cdot B}{C\cdot D} = \frac{A}{C} \cdot \frac{B}{D}.
                </me>
                First, we split <m>P</m> and <m>t</m> in the numerator and denominator, then use the rule above to separate the fraction, like so
                <me>
                    \frac{dP}{dt}
                    = \underset{not\ separated}{\underbrace{\frac{Pt}{P^2 + 1}}} 
                    = \frac{P\cdot t}{(P^2 + 1) \cdot (1) }
                    = \underset{separated}{\underbrace{
                        {\color{blue} \frac{P}{P^2 + 1} } \left({\color{green} \frac{t}{1} }\right)
                    }}
                </me>
                and the equation is <em>separable</em>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    
    </example>
    
    <example xml:id="example-separate-a-sum-of-exponents"><title> Separate a Sum of Exponents </title>
    
        <p>
            Write the differential equation in separable form.
            <me> \frac{dy}{dx} = 11e^{4x + 3y} </me>
        </p>
        
        <solution>
            <p>
                Applying the rule
                <me>
                    e^{A + B} = e^{A} \cdot e^{B}
                </me>
                to this differential equation allows us to show it is separable as follows:
                <!-- <me>
                    \frac{dy}{dx} = \color{blue}{\underset{f(x)}{\underset{\uparrow}{ \vphantom{|} 11e^{4x} }}} \cdot \color{green}{\underset{g(y)}{\underset{\uparrow}{ \vphantom{|} e^{3y} }}}
                </me> -->
                <me>
                    \frac{dy}{dx}
                    = \underset{not\ separated}{\underbrace{11e^{4x + 3y}}} 
                    = 11(e^{4x} \cdot e^{3y})
                    = \underset{separated}{\underbrace{
                        {\color{blue} 11e^{4x} } \cdot {\color{green} e^{3y} }
                    }}.
                </me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    
    </example>
    
